body_raw:
Suppose we have the following vector field in $\mathbb{R}^3$ : $$\vec{F}(x,y,z) = F_x \hat{x}+F_y \hat{y}+F_z \hat{z}$$ where $\hat{x}$ , $\hat{y}$ , and $\hat{z}$ are unit vectors in each of the directions on a Cartesian coordinate system, and $F_x$ , $F_y$ , and $F_z$ are some scalar-valued functions of $x$ , $y$ , and $z$ . Equivalently, in spherical coordinates, $$\vec{F}(r,	heta,\phi) = F_r \hat{r}+F_	heta \hat{	heta}+F_\phi \hat{\phi}$$ where $\hat{x}$ , $\hat{y}$ , and $\hat{z}$ have been transformed into $\hat{r}$ , $\hat{	heta}$ , and $\hat{\phi}$ using the relations here , and $F_r$ , $F_	heta$ , and $F_\phi$ are some combinations of $F_x$ , $F_y$ , and $F_z$ that result from this transformation. My question is about deriving the formula for the divergence of this vector field in spherical coordinates. The divergence is commonly written as $$Div(\vec{F})=\vec{
abla} \cdot \vec{F}$$ One approach I can take to derive the formula is shown here , where I rewrite $$Div(\vec{F})=\vec{
abla} \cdot \vec{F} =  rac{\partial F_x}{\partial x} +  rac{\partial F_y}{\partial y} +  rac{\partial F_z}{\partial z}$$ and convert $ rac{\partial}{\partial x} =  rac{\partial r}{\partial x}  rac{\partial}{\partial r} +  rac{\partial 	heta}{\partial x}  rac{\partial}{\partial 	heta} +  rac{\partial \phi}{\partial x}  rac{\partial}{\partial \phi}$ , and $F_x(x,y,z)=F_x(r,	heta,\phi)$ , and so on. Then, I eventually get the correct formula: $$Div(\vec{F}) =  rac{1}{r^2}  rac{\partial (r^2 F_r)}{\partial r} +  rac{1}{r \sin(	heta)}  rac{\partial (F_	heta \sin(	heta))}{\partial 	heta} +  rac{1}{r \sin(	heta)}  rac{\partial F_\phi}{\partial \phi}$$ However, I would like to know why the following does not work . I can rewrite the gradient operator as: $$\vec{
abla} = rac{\partial}{\partial x} \hat{x} +  rac{\partial}{\partial y} \hat{y} +  rac{\partial}{\partial z} \hat{z} =  rac{\partial}{\partial r} \hat{r} +  rac{1}{r}  rac{\partial}{\partial 	heta} \hat{	heta} +  rac{1}{r \sin{	heta}} rac{\partial}{\partial \phi} \hat{\phi}$$ Then: $$Div(\vec{F}) = \vec{
abla} \cdot \vec{F} = ( rac{\partial}{\partial r} \hat{r} +  rac{1}{r}  rac{\partial}{\partial 	heta} \hat{	heta} +  rac{1}{r \sin{	heta}} rac{\partial}{\partial \phi} \hat{\phi}) \cdot (F_r \hat{r}+F_	heta \hat{	heta}+F_\phi \hat{\phi})$$ Finally, using the relations between the unit vectors for an orthogonal coordinate system (e.g. $\hat{r} \cdot \hat{	heta} = 0$ , $\hat{\phi} \cdot \hat{\phi} = 1$ , etc.), I end up with $$Div(\vec{F}) =  rac{\partial F_r}{\partial r} +  rac{1}{r}  rac{\partial F_	heta}{\partial 	heta} +  rac{1}{r \sin(	heta)}  rac{\partial F_\phi}{\partial \phi}$$ which is not the correct formula. I would like to know where my fault is, and whether this "dot product notation" for divergence is only applicable when evaluated in the Cartesian system. And, if so, why?

